Geometric First Principles of Molecular Structure and Chemical Bonds: A Unified Formulation within the TDMU 2.31 Framework

Abstract: Within the framework of the Topological Dynamical Membrane Universe model (TDMU 2.31), this paper systematically reconstructs the theoretical foundation of molecular structure and chemical bonding using only purely geometric concepts such as nodes, directed edges, shared links, and dangling link ports. Covalent bonds are interpreted as localized shared-link networks of high saturation and high orientation; ionic bonds as a macroscopic manifestation of link density gradients; metallic bonds as a statistical sea of delocalized shared links; and van der Waals forces as the fluctuating average of transient reconnections. Carbon allotropes (diamond, graphite, graphene) become textbook cases of spatial orientation strategies for dangling link ports. This paper further extends the framework to the geometric essence of oxidation reactions and the geometric criterion for transparency, and based on TDMU geometric logic, proposes several predictions not yet experimentally verified, including an oxygen-based diamond-like structure ("oxygen diamond") and a negative thermal expansion superconductor. Each prediction comes with clear falsification conditions. This framework completely eliminates reliance on classical concepts such as "electron clouds," "orbital hybridization," and "electron transfer."

Keywords: Topological Dynamical Membrane Universe model; molecular structure; chemical bonds; dangling link ports; shared links; carbon allotropes; oxygen diamond

1. Introduction

Traditional theories of molecular structure and chemical bonding are built upon quantum mechanics: concepts such as electron cloud overlap, orbital hybridization, molecular orbital energy levels, and electronegativity differences form the cornerstones of modern chemistry. However, without exception, these concepts rely on a mixed language of wave functions in continuous space and classical mechanics, presenting a fundamental paradigmatic difference from the combinatorial network ontology of TDMU.

In TDMU 2.31, all material structures are topological knots on the membrane, and all interactions are geometric properties of shared links. This paper aims to extend this geometric language to the molecular scale, demonstrating a unified geometric description from covalent bonds to intermolecular forces—and using the element carbon, oxidation reactions, and transparency as case studies to showcase the framework's explanatory and predictive power beyond classical chemistry.

Core Thesis:
Chemical bonds are stable shared-link networks established between the dangling link ports (spikes) of two atomic nuclei (topological knots). The type of bond is determined by the relative weights of the five geometric parameters of the shared links. Chemical reactions are the re-weaving of dangling link ports; oxidation is the process of ports being forcibly locked; transparency is the geometric state of having "no excitable dangling link ports."

2. Fundamental Geometric Definitions and Glossary

2.1 Atomic Nuclei as Topological Knots

In TDMU, an atomic nucleus is a stable topological knot formed from numerous electron-bricks and underlying proto-bricks according to recursive weaving rules (TDMU 2.31 Definition 7.2). Its structure exhibits a universal binary layered pattern:

Rigid Core: Composed of electron-bricks in the closest packing arrangement, providing high binding energy to resist disintegration.
Soft Outer Layer: Composed of proto-bricks or small topological knots floating on the core surface, attached via defect complementarity.
This "core–shell" structure is a universal design of recursive weaving, applicable to all levels from electron-bricks to baryon-bricks and atomic nuclei.

2.2 Dangling Link Ports (Spikes)

Definition 2.1 (Dangling Link Port): Directed edge ports extending outward from the surface of an atomic nucleus topological knot due to weaving imperfection, which have not established stable shared links with any neighboring topological knots. These ports are the geometric carriers of chemical bonds.

Key Properties:

Dangling link ports are an affirmative formulation of "defect"—it is not "what is missing," but "what is extra" (unsaturated link ends protruding outward).
The number, spatial orientation, and link saturation of ports determine the atom's capacity and manner of bonding with other atoms.
The "activation state" of ports can change with external conditions (pressure, temperature, shear stress)—some ports curl inward at ambient pressure (lone pairs) and can be forcibly everted to participate in bonding under extreme conditions (see Section 7).
Chemical Correspondence: Number of ports ↔ number of valence electrons; port orientation ↔ hybrid orbital direction; port saturation requirement ↔ octet rule.

