3. Geometric Classification of Chemical Bonds

3.1 Covalent Bond

Definition 3.1 (Covalent Bond): A localized shared-link channel of high saturation (S→1) and high orientation (O→1) formed when the dangling link ports of two atomic nucleus topological knots undergo geometrically complementary matching and reconnect through defect complementarity.

Geometric Correspondence of Bond Order:

Single bond: 1 high-saturation shared-link channel
Double bond: 2 parallel channels
Triple bond: 3 parallel channels
Bond dissociation energy corresponds to the number of reconnection steps required to simultaneously sever these high-saturation links.
Geometric Origin of Molecular Shape: The spatial orientation of dangling link ports is determined by the weaving curvature of the atomic nucleus surface, independent of the concept of "orbital hybridization." Carbon's 4 ports automatically assume a regular tetrahedral distribution in the lowest-stress configuration; nitrogen's 3 ports a trigonal pyramid; oxygen's 2 ports a bent geometry.

3.2 Ionic Bond

Definition 3.2 (Ionic Bond): When there is an extreme quantitative difference in the density of dangling link ports between two atomic nuclei, the density gradient (∇ρ) of shared links reaches a maximum. This non-uniformity of link distribution macroscopically manifests as an isotropic attractive field.

Metal atom: Surface possesses an excess of dangling link ports (low saturation)
Non-metal atom: Surface severely lacks ports (high saturation demand)
Essence of the bond: Stress equilibration from high-density region to low-density region
Characteristic: Total number of links is large, but orientation degree is extremely low (O→0); thus the attraction is isotropic with no fixed direction.
3.3 Metallic Bond

Definition 3.3 (Metallic Bond): The dangling link ports of numerous atomic nuclei are not locked pairwise but interweave into a delocalized sea of shared links covering the entire lattice (the static version of TDMU Definition 8.7).

Geometric Characteristics:

Total Links N: Extremely large (macroscopic scale)
Link Orientation O: Approaches zero (completely isotropic)
Link Saturation S: Extremely low (most ports are semi-open)
Geometric Origin of Ductility: Under shear stress, the shared link network with extremely low saturation can re-weave itself through local reconnections without needing to simultaneously sever high-saturation links—the network flows like a liquid without losing overall connectivity.

Geometric Origin of Electrical Conductivity (Normal State): When the directed shared link flux moves through this low-saturation sea, it is scattered by thermally fluctuating dangling link ports (dynamic spikes). Electrical resistance is the statistical value of the scattering reconnection frequency.

3.4 Van der Waals Force

Definition 3.4 (Van der Waals Force): The statistical average effect produced by instantaneous, fragile contact reconnections occurring between the dangling link ports of two adjacent topological knots due to loop density fluctuations (thermal fluctuations) on the membrane.

Geometric Characteristics:

Total Links N: Extremely low (1–2 per instance)
Link Fragility V: Extremely high (disconnects under minimal perturbation)
Essence: Statistical projection of high-frequency dynamic reconnections.
3.5 Hydrogen Bond

Definition 3.5 (Hydrogen Bond): When the surface of a hydrogen nucleus (which has only one dangling link port already forming a high-saturation link with another atom) still possesses residual unsaturated curvature, this port can act as a "geometric acceptor," forming a medium-saturation, medium-orientation shared link with the dangling links of a neighboring electron-rich atom (high port density).

The hydrogen bond is an intermediate state on the geometric continuum between covalent and ionic bonds, a natural manifestation of TDMU's "continuous spectrum" thinking at the molecular scale.

4. Water and Ice: A Unified Geometric Explanation of States of Matter, Transparency, and Fractal Structure

4.1 Water → Ice Phase Transition: Global Freezing of the Shared Link Network

Liquid water: Each water molecule forms a dynamic, high-fragility hydrogen-bond shared-link network with surrounding molecules. Links constantly disconnect and reconnect, with extremely short average lifetimes (picosecond scale), macroscopically manifesting as fluidity.

Ice (Phase Transition): When the loop density (temperature) falls below a critical value, thermal fluctuations are no longer sufficient to break the hydrogen-bond shared links. The reconnection frequency of the entire network ν_reconnection → 0—the dangling link ports of all water molecules enter a "configurational freezing" state.

Geometric Essence: The water-to-ice transition and superconductivity are geometrically the same type of phase transition—only superconductivity freezes the phase of conducting shared links, while ice freezing freezes the configuration of hydrogen-bond shared links.

Geometric Reason Ice Floats on Water: Upon freezing, the 4 dangling link ports of each water molecule are forced into a regular tetrahedral orientation (O→1). The resulting three-dimensional network is an open framework (analogous to the diamond structure); the total number of links per unit volume decreases → density decreases.

4.2 Geometric Criterion for Transparency

Definition 4.1 (Transparency): The light transmittance of a material is determined by the minimum number of reconnection steps required for a dangling link port in the shared link network to detach from its current locked configuration. If this step count exceeds the maximum reconnection cascade depth that photon perturbations can induce, the material is transparent.

Equivalent Formulation: If there are no dangling link ports in the network whose reconnection step threshold for detachment is below the critical value, incident light perturbations cannot be absorbed or scattered.

Why Ice is Transparent: Ice's hydrogen bond network is perfectly saturated—each oxygen's dangling ports are occupied by two hydrogens, and each hydrogen's port is locked to an oxygen. The number of reconnection steps required for any port in the entire crystal to detach is extremely high (>10² steps). Photons passing through only cause instantaneous elastic deformation of the links (refraction) and exit unaltered.

Why Snow is White: Snow is a porous fractal aggregate of ice. Each microcrystal surface possesses a large number of dangling link ports (surface defects) whose detachment requires extremely low reconnection steps, producing strong scattering of visible light (Lambertian reflection), macroscopically appearing white.

Why Metals are Opaque: Metals possess a vast delocalized sea of shared links with low saturation—ports require very few reconnection steps (≤3 steps) to detach; photon energy easily triggers absorption and re-emission (reflection).

4.3 Geometric Origin of Snowflake Fractals

Snowflake fractals are the frozen traces of "diffusion-limited reconnection of dangling link ports" projected onto two dimensions. After the initial hexagonal ice crystal nucleus forms (corresponding to the hexagonal symmetry of the oxygen tetrahedron in 2D projection), surrounding water molecules perform random walks in the gas phase. The local density of dangling link ports at protruding tips is higher than in recesses; newly arriving molecules preferentially reconnect at the tips, causing accelerated tip growth and iterative branching. The macroscopic fractal morphology is a geometric mapping of the reconnection probability distribution.

